etymologies: late 18th century; earliest use found in Gazetteer & New Daily Advertiser. Probably from Dutch kanaster, †canaster, specific semantic development of kanaster reed basket from either Portuguese canastro reed basket or perhaps Spanish canastro reed basket (although this is first attested slightly later: 1617 or earlier), both ultimately from ancient Greek κάναστρον

definitions: A kind of tobacco made of the dried leaves, coarsely broken.
